Override the `CreateWindow` method in your `App` class and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created       += (s, e) => Log("Created");
        window.Activated     += (s, e) => Log("Activated");
        window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Log("Deactivated");
        window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Log("Stopped");
        window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Log("Resumed");
        window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Log("Destroying");
        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Log($"Backgrounding (state: {e.State})");

        return window;
    }

    static void Log(string evt)
        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($"[Window] {evt} at {DateTime.Now:T}");
}
```

**Typical transition order:**

| Scenario | Events |
|---|---|
| App launch | `Created → Activated` |
| Sent to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |
| App closed | `Destroying` |

> **Note:** `Backgrounding` fires on **iOS/macOS** only and provides a `state` dictionary you can use to persist data before suspension.
